Step 1: Install NginxUnlike Tomcat, Nginx is available directly inside your standard Linux package repositories.
For Amazon Linux 2023 / RHEL:bashsudo dnf install nginx -y
Use code with caution.For Ubuntu / Debian:bashsudo apt update && sudo apt install nginx -y
Use code with caution.

Step 2: Configure the Reverse Proxy RoutingTo make Nginx talk to Tomcat, 
we must edit Nginx's main configuration file.Open the configuration file:bashsudo nano /etc/nginx/nginx.conf
Use code with caution.Find the server { ... } block that listens on port 80, and update its location / section to point directly to your Tomcat backend 
IP and port:nginxlocation / {
    proxy_pass http://<YOUR_TOMCAT_SERVER_PRIVATE_IP>:8080;
    proxy_set_header Host $host;
    proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
}
Use code with caution.

Step 3: Start and Enable the Nginx ServiceJust like Tomcat, Nginx runs as a background system service.bashsudo systemctl start nginx
sudo systemctl enable nginx
sudo systemctl status nginx
Use code with caution.

Step 4: Open Port 80 in Your FirewallSince Nginx handles standard web traffic, you must allow incoming connections on port 80 through your Linux firewall
 (and your AWS EC2 Security Group).For Amazon Linux / RHEL:bashsudo firewall-cmd --zone=public --permanent --add-service=http
sudo firewall-cmd --reload
Use code with caution.Once this is done, you can type http://<YOUR_NGINX_PUBLIC_IP> into your browser, 
and you will see the Tomcat welcome page without needing to type :8080 at the end!
